label: recruitment
description:
It's the rate on which new individuals establishes in a certain
community either by new born individuals or immigration.[Cerrado link] ; The process by which new individuals are added to a population, whether by birth and maturation or by immigration. [Wikipedia]

label: Plant Mortality
description: The death of plants caused by fire.

label: Plant resprout
description: It's when the fire event influence the plant individuals to resprout, that is, the fire can induce the growth of new branches as well the vegetative reproduction of some fire resistant species.

label: vegetation stratum
description: There is a maximum of seven layers or strata at any one site. There may be one emergent layer [E] dominated by trees or less commonly shrubs [see below]; There may be up to three tree layers [in addition to an emergent layer]: canopy [T1], subcanopy [T2], low tree layer [T3] but is not always present, particularly in low woodlands. There may be two layers that are dominated by shrubs: tallest shrub layer [S1]. This may also include some low trees. If only one shrub layer is present, then it is S1; lower shrub layer [S2] This may be referred to as a sub-shrub layer, often not recognised apart from shrub dominated vegetation such as heathlands. There is one ground layer [G] although it may be absent. This layer may contain graminoids, forbs, sprawling vines and other plants that are short in stature and overlap in height with the grasses.

label: calculated
description: The measurement is calculated by incorporating one or more measured values into an equation other than a ratio, fractional change or indexed calculation.

label: physiology parameter
description: Experimentally determined parameter of the physiology of an organism, e.g. substrate spectrum.

label: morphology parameter
description: Experimentally determined parameter of the morphology of an organism, e.g. size & shape.

label: molecular genetics
description: The structure and function of genes at a molecular level.

label: duration
description: A temporal measurement of the time between two specified points.

label: individual
description: An individual used as a specimen in an experiment, from which a material sample was derived.

label: treatment
description: A planned process intended to modify or alter a condition or characteristic of an organism or individual.

label: storage organ
description: [no definition]

label: substrate
description: A substrate is the surface on which material, such as an organism, is grown or attached.

label: epiphyte
description: [no definition]

label: vegetation reflectance
description: [no definition]

description: [no definition]

label: stable isotope
description: Some isotopes are radioactive, and are therefore described as radioisotopes or radionuclides, while others have never been observed to undergo radioactive decay and are described as stable isotopes or stable nuclides. For example, 14C is a radioactive form of carbon while 12C and 13C are stable isotopes. Elements are composed of one or more naturally occurring isotopes. All the known stable isotopes occur naturally on Earth. Isotope analysis is the determination of isotopic signature, the relative abundances of isotopes of a given element in a particular sample. For biogenic substances in particular, significant variations of isotopes of C, N and O can occur.

label: disturbance (event)
description: External event affecting the ecosystem

label: seedling establishment
description: [no definition]

label: vegetation
description: [Henderson's] n. the plant cover of an area, con­sidered generally, and not taxonomically.

label: fine root
description: Primary roots usually less than 2 mm diameter that have the function of water and nutrient uptake. They are often heavily branched and support mycorrhizas. These roots may be short lived, but are replaced by the plant in an ongoing process of root 'turnover'

label: mycorrhizae
description: [Henderson's] mycorrhiza n. symbiotic association between plant roots and certain fungi, in which a sheath of fungal tissue (the mantle) encloses the smallest rootlets. There are two main types. In ectomycorrhizas the fungal hyphae penetrate between the cells of the epidermis and cortex. In endomy­corrhizas they penetrate the plant cells themselves and an external fungal sheath is often lacking. Mycorrhizas are essential for optimum growth and development in many trees, shrubs and herbaceous plants.

label: woody plants
description: [no definition]

label: dead wood biomass
description: Dead trees or dead branches or wood on a tree

label: clonal growth
description: [no definition]

label: vegetative growth
description: [no definition]

label: dispersal
description: Biological dispersal refers to both the movement of individuals (animals, plants, fungi, bacteria, etc.) from their birth site to their breeding site, as well as the movement from one breeding site to another. Disperal is also used to describe the movement of propagules such as seeds and spores.

label: seed dispersal
description: [no definition]

label: generation time
description: [Henderson's] [1] of cells, the time between formation of a somatic cell by mitosis and its own division; [2] of human and animal populations, the average span of time between the birth of parents and the birth of their offspring; [3] of microor­ganisms, time taken for one cell to divide and produce two new cells, often expressed as the time taken for the population to double.

label: survival
description: [GEMET] The act or fact of surviving or condition of having survived.

label: survival rate
description: [OBI] A measurement data that represents the percentage of people or animals in a study or treatment group who are alive for a given period of time after diagnosis or initiation of monitoring.

label: production
description: [Henderson's] n. in ecology, the assimilation of nutrients into biomass. see net primary production, primary production.

label: chemical defence
description: [Henderson's] unpalatable or toxic chemicals, such as astringent tannins and toxic alkaloids, produced by plants in their tissues to deter herbivores.

label: competition
description: [Henderson's] n. (1) active demand by two or more organisms for a material or con­dition, so that both are inhibited by the demand, e.g. plants competing for light and water, cf. amensalism; (2) active demand by two or more substances for the same binding site on an enzyme or receptor. alt. competitive binding.

label: biomass dry
description: [no definition]

label: biomass fresh
description: [no definition]

label: biomass moisture content
description: [no definition]

label: stomatal conductance
description: stomatal conductance, usually measured in mmol m⁻² s⁻¹, is the measure of the rate of passage of carbon dioxide [CO2] entering, or water vapor exiting through the stomata of a leaf.

label: environmental stress
description: [APAONTO] Naturally occurring or experimentally manipulated qualities of the physical environment which result in strain or disequilibrium. Consider also other specific terms [e.g., CROWDING, NOISE EFFECTS].

label: biomass allocation
description: [no definition]

label: cell size
description: [CRISP]* the physical dimensions of a cell; may refer to changes in dimensions correlated with physiological or pathological changes in cells.

label: relative growth rate
description: [no definition]

label: life form
description: [Henderson's] the typical adult form of a species.

label: habitat disturbance
description: [no definition]

label: dry matter content
description: [no definition]

label: osmotic pressure
description: [Henderson's] a measure of the osmotic activity of a solution, deﬁned as the minimum pressure that must be exerted to prevent the passage of pure solvent into the solution when the two are separated by a semipermeable membrane. Osmotic pressure is proportional to solute concentration.

label: surface area
description: [HUPSON] The area of a surface of some entity.

label: vapor pressure
description: The partial pressure of water vapour in the atmosphere. For a liquid or solid, the pressure of the vapour in equilibrium with the liquid or solid.

label: reflectance
description: The ratio of the total amount of radiation, as of light, reflected by a surface to the total amount of radiation incident on the surface.

label: temporal pattern
description: [no definition]

label: remote sensing
description: 1) The scientific detection, recognition, inventory and analysis of land and water area by the use of distant sensors or recording devices such as photography, thermal scanners, radar, etc. 2) Complex of techniques for the remote measure of electromagnetic energy emitted by objects.

label: aquatic
description: Any watery environment, from small to large, from pond to ocean, in which plants and animals interact with the chemical and physical features of the environment.

label: terrestrial
description: [no definition]

label: layer
description: [Henderson's] n. horizontal stratum in a plant com­munity. The following are usually distin­guished: the tree layer or canopy, the shrub layer, comprising the shrubby understorey, the herb layer of grass and herbaceous plants, and the ground [moss] layer, com­prising the ground surface and lichens and mosses.

description: [no definition]

description: [no definition]

description: [no definition]

description: [no definition]

label: above ground biomass

label: air carbon dioxide concentration
description: A concentration is the amount of a substance in a given volume, thus CO2 concentration is a measure of the percentage of the atmosphere that is composed of CO2 [e.g., 380 ppm].

label: flowering date
description: date of flowering

label: hydraulic conductivity
description: Hydraulic conductance is a measure of the efficiency of bulk flow through a material, and defined as the flow rate per unit pressure driving force.

label: leaf age
description: [no definition]

label: leaf area index
description: [Henderson's] of a given area of vegetation, the total area of photosynthetic leaf surface divided by the area of soil covered.

label: leaf area ratio
description: [Henderson's] the ratio of the photosynthetic surface area of a leaf to its dry weight.

label: leaf longevity time
description: [Kihachiro Kikuzawa] Leaf longevity is an integral part of a quintet of highly intercorrelated and functionally interdependent traits that organize the function of leaves as photosynthetic organs: photosynthetic capacity, A max

label: saturated hydraulic conductivity
description: [no definition]

label: saturated water content

label: seed longevity time
description: [no definition]

label: seed viability ratio
description: The viability of a seed after storage or treatment.

label: soil water content
description: Volume of water of total soil volume

label: soil water potential
description: [no definition]

label: water potential

description: [no definition]

label: resource availability
description: [S. D. Tiegs] Resource availability is an important ecosystem attribute that can influence species distributions\ \ and ecosystem processes... , "[Allen H. Hurlbert] Resource availability is an important constraint on community structure. Some authors have suggested\ \ it conceptually links two of the most basic patterns in ecology, the species-area relationship and\ \ the latitudinal gradient in species richness... , "[Marja A. van Staalduinen] Resource availability is an important factor affecting the capacity of compensatory growth after\ \ grazing...

label: fire severity index
description: The effect of a fire on ecosystem properties, usually defined by the degree of soil heating or mortality and damage of vegetation.

label: nitrogen symbiotic fixation
description: [no definition]

label: seedling
description: A young plant that is grown from a seed

label: defence
description: A trait or behaviour that is useful for repelling an enemy.

label: Hagen Poiseuille equation
description: In fluid dynamics, the Hagen Poiseuille equation is a physical law that gives the pressure drop in a fluid flowing through a long cylindrical pipe. The assumptions of the equation are that the flow is laminar viscous and incompressible and the flow is through a constant circular cross-section that is substantially longer than its diameter. The equation is also known as the Hagen Poiseuille law, Poiseuille law and Poiseuille equation. ... In standard fluid dynamics notation: Delta P = \frac{8 \mu L Q}{ \pi r^4} or \Delta P = \frac{128 \mu L Q}{ \pi d^4} where: P is the pressure drop L is the length of pipe is the dynamic viscosity Q is the volumetric flow rate r is the radius d is the diameter Physics notation \Phi = \frac{dV}{dt} = v \pi R^{2} = \frac{\pi R^{4}}{8 \eta} \left[ \frac{- \Delta P}{\Delta x}\right] = \frac{\pi R^{4}}{8 \eta} \frac{ |\Delta P|}{L} where: V is a volume of the liquid poured [cubic meters] t is the time [seconds] v is mean fluid velocity along the length of the tube [meters/second] x is a distance in direction of flow [meters] R is the internal radius of the tube [meters] P is the pressure difference between the two ends [pascals] L is the total length of the tube in the x direction [meters]. source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poiseuille_equation

label: establishment
description: The process by which a plant becomes established in a new habitat.

label: water holding capacity
formatted label and identifier: water holding capacity [Interlinking Ontology for Biological Concepts:200906064703668091]
description: [no definition]

label: seed bank
description: A repository of seeds maintained under optimal conditions that ensure long term storage, intended for use as a source of replenishment of seed stock or plant genetic material.

label: electron transport
description: The process by which ELECTRONS are transported from a reduced substrate to molecular OXYGEN. (From Bennington, Saunders Dictionary and Encyclopedia of Laboratory Medicine and Technology, 1984, p270)

label: gas
description: The vapor state of matter; nonelastic fluids in which the molecules are in free movement and their mean positions far apart. Gases tend to expand indefinitely, to diffuse and mix readily with other gases, to have definite relations of volume, temperature, and pressure, and to condense or liquefy at low temperatures or under sufficient pressure. (Grant & Hackh's Chemical Dictionary, 5th ed)

label: tensile strength
description: The maximum stress a material subjected to a stretching load can withstand without tearing.

label: compressive strength
description: The maximum compression a material can withstand without failure.

label: mechanical phenomena
description: The properties and processes of materials that affect their behavior under force.

label: Ribulose-Bisphosphate Carboxylase
description: A carboxy-lyase that plays a key role in photosynthetic carbon assimilation in the CALVIN-BENSON CYCLE by catalyzing the formation of 3-phosphoglycerate from ribulose 1,5-biphosphate and CARBON DIOXIDE. It can also utilize OXYGEN as a substrate to catalyze the synthesis of 2-phosphoglycolate and 3-phosphoglycerate in a process referred to as photorespiration.

label: Models, Theoretical
description: Theoretical representations that simulate the behavior or activity of systems, processes, or phenomena. They include the use of mathematical equations, computers, and other electronic equipment.

label: tissue
description: Multicellular anatomical structure that consists of many cells of one or a few types, arranged in an extracellular matrix such that their long-range organisation is at least partly a repetition of their short-range organisation.

label: water
description: An oxygen hydride consisting of an oxygen atom that is covalently bonded to two hydrogen atoms.

label: dioxygen, oxygen
description: [no definition]

label: carbon dioxide
description: A one-carbon compound with formula CO2 in which the carbon is attached to each oxygen atom by a double bond. A colourless, odourless gas under normal conditions, it is produced during respiration by all animals, fungi and microorganisms that depend directly or indirectly on living or decaying plants for food.

label: carbohydrate
description: Any member of the class of organooxygen compounds that is a polyhydroxy-aldehyde or -ketone or a lactol resulting from their intramolecular condensation [monosaccharides]; substances derived from these by reduction of the carbonyl group [alditols], by oxidation of one or more hydroxy groups to afford the corresponding aldehydes, ketones, or carboxylic acids, or by replacement of one or more hydroxy group[s] by a hydrogen atom; and polymeric products arising by intermolecular acetal formation between two or more such molecules [disaccharides, polysaccharides and oligosaccharides]. Carbohydrates contain only carbon, hydrogen and oxygen atoms; prior to any oxidation or reduction, most have the empirical formula Cm[H2O]n. Compounds obtained from carbohydrates by substitution, etc., are known as carbohydrate derivatives and may contain other elements. Cyclitols are generally not regarded as carbohydrates.

label: lipid
description: Lipids' is a loosely defined term for substances of biological origin that are soluble in nonpolar solvents. They consist of saponifiable lipids, such as glycerides [fats and oils] and phospholipids, as well as nonsaponifiable lipids, principally steroids.

label: polysaccharide
description: A biomacromolecule consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically. This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.

label: chlorophyll a
description: [no definition]

label: iron atom
description: An iron group element atom that has atomic number 26.

label: manganese atom
description: [no definition]

label: calcium atom
description: [no definition]

label: carotenoid
description: One of a class of tetraterpenoids [C40], formally derived from the acyclic parent, ψ,ψ-carotene by hydrogenation, dehydrogenation, cyclization, oxidation, or combination of these processes. This class includes carotenes, xanthophylls and certain compounds that arise from rearrangement of the skeleton of ψ,ψ-carotene or by loss of part of this structure. Retinoids are excluded.

label: chlorine atom
description: [no definition]

label: molecular
description: Any constitutionally or isotopically distinct atom, molecule, ion, ion pair, radical, radical ion, complex, conformer etc., identifiable as a separately distinguishable entity.

label: salt
description: An ionic compound that results from the neutralization of an acid and a base.

label: magnesium atom
description: [no definition]

label: nitrogen atom
description: [no definition]

label: polyphenol
description: Members of the class of phenols that contain 2 or more benzene rings each of which is substituted by at least one hydroxy group.

label: potassium atom

label: sodium atom
description: [no definition]

label: sulfur atom
description: [no definition]

label: tannin
description: Any of a group of astringent polyphenolic vegetable principles or compounds, chiefly complex glucosides of catechol and pyrogallol.

label: micronutrient
description: Any nutrient required in small quantities by organisms throughout their life in order to orchestrate a range of physiological functions.

label: xanthophyll
description: A subclass of carotenoids consisting of the oxygenated carotenes.

label: zinc atom
description: [no definition]

label: boron atom
description: [no definition]

label: selenium atom
description: [no definition]

label: silicon atom
description: [no definition]

label: carbon atom
description: [no definition]

label: cobalt atom
description: A cobalt group element atom that has atomic number 27.

label: chlorophyll b
description: [no definition]

label: starch
description: The most important reserve polysaccharide found in plants. It is a glucan consisting of amylose and amylopectin.

label: chromium atom
description: A chromium group element atom that has atomic number 24.

label: nickel atom
description: Chemical element [nickel group element atom] with atomic number 28.

label: phosphorus atom
description: [no definition]

label: molybdenum atom
description: [no definition]

label: copper atom
description: [no definition]

label: chlorophyll
description: A family of magnesium porphyrins, defined by the presence of a fifth ring beyond the four pyrrole-like rings. The rings can have various side chains which usually include a long phytol chain.

label: aluminium atom
description: [no definition]

label: gallic acid
description: A trihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydroxy groups are at positions 3, 4, and 5.

label: nutrient
description: A nutrient is a food component that an organism uses to survive and grow.

label: fuel
description: An energy-rich substance that can be transformed with release of usable energy.

label: oxygen-18 atom
description: The stable isotope of oxygen with relative atomic mass 17.999160 and 0.205 atom percent natural abundance.

label: phenol
description: Organic aromatic compounds having one or more hydroxy groups attached to a benzene or other arene ring.

label: macronutrient
description: Any nutrient required in large quantities by organisms throughout their life in order to orchestrate a range of physiological functions.

label: monosaccharide
description: Parent monosaccharides are polyhydroxy aldehydes H[CH[OH]]nC[=O]H or polyhydroxy ketones H‒[CHOH]n‒C[=O][CHOH]m‒H with three or more carbon atoms. The generic term 'monosaccharide' [as opposed to oligosaccharide or polysaccharide] denotes a single unit, without glycosidic connection to other such units. It includes aldoses, dialdoses, aldoketoses, ketoses and diketoses, as well as deoxy sugars, provided that the parent compound has a [potential] carbonyl group.

label: protein
description: A biological macromolecule minimally consisting of one polypeptide chain synthesized at the ribosome.

label: disaccharide
description: A compound in which two monosaccharides are joined by a glycosidic bond.

label: carbon-13 atom
description: [no definition]

label: nitrogen-15 atom
description: The stable isotope of nitrogen with relative atomic mass 15.000109. The least abundant [0.368 atom percent] isotope of naturally occurring nitrogen.

label: glyceride
description: Any ester resulting from the condensation of one or more of the hydroxy groups of glycerol [propane-1,2,3-triol] with fatty acids.

label: hemicellulose
description: Hemicelluloses are polysaccharides in plant cell walls that have β-[1→4]-linked backbones with an equatorial configuration. Hemicelluloses include xyloglucans, xylans, mannans and glucomannans, and β-[1→3,1→4]-glucans.

label: amorphous cellulose
description: A [1→4]-β-D-glucan [cellulose] in amorphous form with a structure consisting of several hundred to over ten thousand D-glucose residues joined by β[1→4] glycosidic linkages.

label: lignin
description: A polyphenylpropanoid derived from three monolignol monomers: trans-p-coumaryl alcohol, coniferol and trans-sinapyl alcohol. There is extensive cross-linking and no defined primary structure.

label: isotope ratio mass spectrometry
description: Mass spectrometry where the relative abundance of isotopes in a sample is determined.

label: stable isotope ratio mass spectrometry
description: Mass spectrometry where the relative abundance of non-radioactive isotopes in a sample is determined.

label: sample drying
description: The process of removing a solvent from a substance.

label: cell
description: A material entity of anatomical origin [part of or deriving from an organism] that has as its parts a maximally connected cell compartment surrounded by a plasma membrane.

label: somatic cell
description: A cell of an organism that does not pass on its genetic material to the organism's offspring (i.e. a non-germ line cell).

label: growth habit
description: A qualitative description of the growth habit of the plant whether erect/semi-erect/prostrate/spreading/semi-spreading.

label: life history
description: A history which includes all the processes during which resources are used by an organism to grow, survive, and reproduce over its lifetime.

label: parasite
description: A symbiotroph that reduces the fitness, survival, or growth of its symbiont, often called a host

label: symbiosis
description: A process during which two living entities engage in a close and long-term biological interaction.

label: soil
description: Soil is an environmental material which is primarily composed of minerals, varying proportions of sand, silt, and clay, organic material such as humus, gases, liquids, and a broad range of resident micro- and macroorganisms.

label: biomass
description: Environmental material derived from living organisms and composed primarily of one or more biomacromolecules.

label: environmental condition
description: An environmental condition is a range of a determinate quality or combination of qualities that are present in an environmental system.

label: arid
description: An environmental condition in which annual precipitation is less than half of annual potential evapotranspiration.

label: atmosphere
description: An atmosphere is a layer of gases surrounding a material body of sufficient mass that is held in place by the gravity of the body.

label: vegetation layer
description: A layer which is determined by a form of vegetation. Usually found in woodlands and forests.

label: snow
description: Snow is an environmental material which is primarily composed of flakes of crystalline water ice.

label: atmospheric carbon dioxide
description: Atmospheric carbon dioxide is an environmental material composed of carbon dioxide in its gaseous form present in an atmosphere.

label: plant litter
description: Leaf litter is dead plant material, such as leaves, bark, needles, and twigs, that has fallen to the ground.

label: flood
description: An unusual accumulation of water above the ground caused by high tide, heavy rain, melting snow or rapid runoff from paved areas.

label: habitat
description: An environmental system which can sustain and allow the growth of an ecological population. A habitat's specificity to an ecological population differentiates it from other environment classes.

label: fire
description: A fire is a process whereby rapid and exothermic oxidation of a material through a combustion process releases heat, light, and other products.

label: flame
description: A portion of gas which is emitted by a fire or other exothermic reaction, is of increased temperature, and typically emits light in the visible range.

label: combustion process
description: Combustion or burning is a high-temperature exothermic redox chemical reaction between a fuel and an oxidant that produces oxidized, often gaseous products, in a mixture termed as smoke.

label: canopy
description: A vegetation layer which is formed by a collection of individual plant crowns, themselves constituting part of the aboveground portion of a plant community.

label: photosynthetically active radiation
description: Photosynthetically active radiation, often abbreviated PAR, designates the spectral range [wave band] of solar radiation from 400 to 700 nanometers that photosynthetic organisms are able to use in the process of photosynthesis. This spectral region corresponds more or less with the range of light visible to the human eye.

label: radiation
description: A process during which energy is emitted or transmitted in the form of waves or particles through space or a material medium.

label: ash
description: An environmental material that is the non-aqueous, non-gaseous residues that remain after something is burned.

label: wood ash
description: The residue powder that is derived from the combustion of wood.

label: transpiration
description: Transpiration is the process of water movement through a plant and its evaporation from aerial parts of that plant, such as from leaves but also from stems and flowers.

label: potential energy
description: Energy possessed by an object because of its position relative to other objects, stresses within itself, its electric charge, or other factors.

label: infrared radiation
description: A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted when molecules change their rotational-vibrational movements, usually at wavelengths between 760 nm and 1 mm.

label: wood
description: [no definition]

label: whole plant phenotype
description: A phenotype of the entire plant, including roots, shoots and leaves, at any stage of its life cycle.

description: [no definition]

description: [no definition]

label: reproduction
description: The production of new individuals that contain some portion of genetic material inherited from one or more parent organisms.

label: developmental process involved in reproduction
description: A developmental process in which a progressive change in the state of some part of an organism, germline or somatic, specifically contributes to its ability to form offspring.

label: cellular component
description: A location, relative to cellular compartments and structures, occupied by a macromolecular machine when it carries out a molecular function. There are two ways in which the gene ontology describes locations of gene products: [1] relative to cellular structures [e.g., cytoplasmic side of plasma membrane] or compartments [e.g., mitochondrion], and [2] the stable macromolecular complexes of which they are parts [e.g., the ribosome].

label: water transport
description: The directed movement of water [H2O] into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

label: nitrogen fixation
description: The process in which nitrogen is taken from its relatively inert molecular form (N2) in the atmosphere and converted into nitrogen compounds useful for other chemical processes, such as ammonia, nitrate and nitrogen dioxide.

label: plant-type cell wall
description: A more or less rigid stucture lying outside the cell membrane of a cell and composed of cellulose and pectin and other organic and inorganic substances.

label: chloroplast
description: A chlorophyll-containing plastid with thylakoids organized into grana and frets, or stroma thylakoids, and embedded in a stroma.

label: photosystem
description: A complex located in a photosynthetic membrane that consists of a photoreaction center associated with accessory pigments and electron carriers. Examples of this component are found in Arabidopsis thaliana and in photosynthetic bacterial and archaeal species.

label: photosystem I reaction center
description: A photochemical system containing P700, the chlorophyll a dimer that functions as a primary electron donor. Functioning as a light-dependent plastocyanin-ferredoxin oxidoreductase, it transfers electrons from plastocyanin to ferredoxin.

label: photosystem II reaction center
description: An integral membrane complex containing P680, the chlorophyll a molecule that functions as a primary electron donor. In the light, functioning as a water-plastoquinone oxidoreductase, it transfers electrons from water to plastoquinone.

label: thylakoid
description: A membranous cellular structure that bears the photosynthetic pigments in plants, algae, and cyanobacteria. In cyanobacteria thylakoids are of various shapes and are attached to, or continuous with, the plasma membrane. In eukaryotes they are flattened, membrane-bounded disk-like structures located in the chloroplasts; in the chloroplasts of higher plants the thylakoids form dense stacks called grana. Isolated thylakoid preparations can carry out photosynthetic electron transport and the associated phosphorylation.

label: response to abiotic stimulus
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an abiotic (not derived from living organisms) stimulus.

label: C4 photosynthesis
description: The combination of atmospheric CO2 with a 3-carbon molecule phosphoenol pyruvate (PEP) in the mesophyll cells to make a 4-carbon acid which is immediately converted to malic acid. The malic acid is then passed across to the bundle sheath cells where it is broken down again to pyruvic acid and CO2. The acid is passed back to the mesophyll cells to be used again, while the CO2 is fed into the reductive pentose-phosphate cycle (Calvin cycle) and converted into sugar and starch. [database_cross_reference: ISBN:0816017360]

label: CAM photosynthesis
description: The combination of atmospheric CO2 with a 3-carbon molecule phosphoenol pyruvate (PEP) to make malic acid. The malic acid is then passed into the vacuole where it is stored until daylight, when it is shuttled back out to be used as a substrate in the light reaction of photosynthesis. [database_cross_reference: ISBN:0582015952]

label: seed germination
description: The physiological and developmental changes that occur in a seed commencing with water uptake [imbibition] and terminating with the elongation of the embryonic axis.

label: photorespiration
description: A light-dependent catabolic process occurring concomitantly with photosynthesis in plants (especially C3 plants) whereby dioxygen (O2) is consumed and carbon dioxide (CO2) is evolved. The substrate is glycolate formed in large quantities in chloroplasts from 2-phosphoglycolate generated from ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate by the action of ribulose-bisphosphate carboxylase; the glycolate enters the peroxisomes where it is converted by glycolate oxidase to glyoxylate which undergoes transamination to glycine. This then passes into the mitochondria where it is decarboxylated forming one molecule of serine for every two molecules of glycine. This pathway also exists in photosynthetic bacteria.

label: pollination
description: The cascade of biological processes occurring in plants beginning when the pollen lands on the female reproductive organs of a plant and continuing up to, but not including, fertilization, as defined by sperm-egg cell fusion.

label: nodulation
description: The formation of nitrogen-fixing root nodules on plant roots.

label: dehiscence
description: The opening of an anther, fruit or other structure, which permits the escape of reproductive bodies contained within it.

label: cellular process
description: Any process that is carried out at the cellular level, but not necessarily restricted to a single cell. For example, cell communication occurs among more than one cell, but occurs at the cellular level.

label: regulation of photosynthesis
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of photosynthesis.

label: seed dormancy
description: The process in which a dormant state is induced, maintained and broken in a seed. Dormancy is characterized by a suspension of physiological activity that can be reactivated.

label: photosynthesis
description: The synthesis by organisms of organic chemical compounds, especially carbohydrates, from carbon dioxide [CO2] using energy obtained from light rather than from the oxidation of chemical compounds.

label: membrane
description: A lipid bilayer along with all the proteins and protein complexes embedded in it and attached to it.

label: death
description: A permanent cessation of all vital functions: the end of life; can be applied to a whole organism or to a part of an organism..

label: host
description: Any organism in which another organism, especially a parasite or symbiont, spends part or all of its life cycle and from which it obtains nourishment and/or protection.

label: Calvin cycle; C3 photosynthesis (reductive pentose-phosphate cycle)
formatted label and identifier: Calvin cycle; C3 photosynthesis (reductive pentose-phosphate cycle) [GO:0019253]
description: The fixation of carbon dioxide (CO2) as glucose in the chloroplasts of C3 plants; uses ATP and NADPH formed in the light reactions of photosynthesis; carbon dioxide reacts with ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate (catalyzed by the function of ribulose-bisphosphate carboxylase) to yield two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate; these are then phosphorylated by ATP to 1,3-bisphosphateglyceraldehyde which, in turn, is then reduced by NADPH to glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate. The glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate is converted to fructose 5-phosphate and ribulose 5-phosphate by aldolase and other enzymes; the ribulose 5-phosphate is phosphorylated by ATP to ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate. [database_cross_reference: ISBN:0198547684]

label: photosynthesis, light reaction
description: The light reactions of photosynthesis, which take place in photosystems II and I. Light energy is harvested and used to power the transfer of electrons among a series of electron donors and acceptors. The final electron acceptor is NADP+, which is reduced to NADPH. NADPH generated from light reactions is used in sugar synthesis in dark reactions. Light reactions also generate a proton motive force across the thylakoid membrane, and the proton gradient is used to synthesize ATP. There are two chemical reactions involved in the light reactions: water oxidation in photosystem II, and NADP reduction in photosystem I.

label: photosynthesis, dark reaction
description: A complex cycle of enzyme-mediated reactions which catalyzes the reduction of carbon dioxide to sugar. As well as carbon dioxide the cycle requires reducing power in the form of reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADP) and chemical energy in the form of adenosine triphosphate (ATP). The reduced NADP (NADPH) and ATP are produced by the 'light' reactions. [database_cross_reference: ISBN:0582015952]

label: asexual reproduction
description: A type of reproduction in which new individuals are produced from a single organism, either from an unfertilized egg or from a single cell or group of cells.

label: electron transport chain
description: A process in which a series of electron carriers operate together to transfer electrons from donors to any of several different terminal electron acceptors.

label: regeneration
description: The regrowth of a lost or destroyed body part, such as an organ or tissue. This process may occur via renewal, repair, and/or growth alone (i.e. increase in size or mass).

label: arbuscular mycorrhizal association
description: A form of mutualism between a fungus and the roots of a vascular plant, where hyphae of the fungus penetrate the plant cell wall and invaginate its cell membrane. Once inside, the fungus forms highly branched structures for nutrient exchange with the plant called arbuscules. Aids in the acquisition by the plant of nutrients such as phosphorus from the soil.

label: growth
description: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.

label: cellular metabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways by which individual cells transform chemical substances.

label: biological process involved in symbiotic interaction, symbiosis
formatted label and identifier: biological process involved in symbiotic interaction [GO:0044403]
description: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association. A process carried out by gene products in an organism that enable the organism to engage in a symbiotic relationship, a more or less intimate association, with another organism. The various forms of symbiosis include parasitism, in which the association is disadvantageous or destructive to one of the organisms; mutualism, in which the association is advantageous, or often necessary to one or both and not harmful to either; and commensalism, in which one member of the association benefits while the other is not affected. However, mutualism, parasitism, and commensalism are often not discrete categories of interactions and should rather be perceived as a continuum of interaction ranging from parasitism to mutualism. In fact, the direction of a symbiotic interaction can change during the lifetime of the symbionts due to developmental changes as well as changes in the biotic/abiotic environment in which the interaction occurs. Microscopic symbionts are often referred to as endosymbionts.

label: biological process involved in interspecies interaction between organisms
formatted label and identifier: biological process involved in interspecies interaction between organisms [GO:0044419]
description: Any process evolved to enable an interaction with an organism of a different species.

label: cellular respiration
description: The enzymatic release of energy from inorganic and organic compounds (especially carbohydrates and fats) which either requires oxygen (aerobic respiration) or does not (anaerobic respiration).

label: rubisco complex, ribulose bisphosphate carboxylase complex
formatted label and identifier: rubisco complex, ribulose bisphosphate carboxylase complex [GO:0048492]
description: A complex containing either both large and small subunits or just small subunits which carries out the activity of producing 3-phosphoglycerate from carbon dioxide and ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate

label: response to stimulus
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus. The process begins with detection of the stimulus and ends with a change in state or activity or the cell or organism.

label: pollen aperture
description: An area where exine is reduced or absent, in the pollen wall.

label: parasitism
description: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association in a relationship in which association is disadvantageous or destructive to one of the organisms.

label: mutualism
description: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association in a relationship in which both organisms benefit from each other.

label: haustorium
description: A projection from a cell or tissue that penetrates the host's cell wall and invaginates the host cell membrane.

label: pollen tube
description: A tubular cell projection that is part of a pollen tube cell and extends from a pollen grain. Carries the male gametes to into or near the ovule.

label: chlorophyll fluorescence
description: The process by which excess light energy absorbed by chlorophyll and not used to drive photosynthesis is re-emitted as light.

label: pain
description: An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience associated with actual or potential tissue damage, or described in terms of such damage.

label: carboxylation
description: Formation of a covalent bond between a substrate and a carboxy group.

label: plants, land plants
description: [no definition]

label: fungi
description: [no definition]

label: cyanobacteria
description: [no definition]

label: suitable, amenable
description: Having the appropriate qualities.

label: shortest diameter
description: The minimum value in a range of values that describe the diameter of an entity.

label: airway conductance
description: The instantaneous rate of gas flow in the airway, expressed as the pressure difference between any given part of the airway and the alveoli; it is the reciprocal of airway resistance.

label: fused
description: A physical quality in which the entity or structure is physically attached or combined with another entity or structure to become a whole.

label: recycle
description: To use again following processing.

label: organ
description: A unique macroscopic (gross) anatomic structure that performs specific functions. It is composed of various tissues. An organ is part of an anatomic system or a body region. Representative examples include the heart, lung, liver, spleen, and uterus.

label: chromosome
description: One of the bodies in the cell nucleus that is the bearer of genes, has the form of a delicate chromatin filament during interphase, contracts to form a compact cylinder segmented into two arms by the centromere during metaphase and anaphase stages of cell division, and is capable of reproducing its physical and chemical structure through successive cell divisions.

label: bacteria
description: Unicellular, prokaryotic organisms that reproduce by cell division and usually have cell walls; can be shaped like spheres, rods or spirals and can be found in virtually any environment.

label: longevity
description: The length or duration of life or viability.

label: combustion
description: The combination of a substance with oxygen that involves the production of heat and light.

label: adaptation
description: The alteration or adjustment in structure or habits, often occurring through natural selection, by which a species becomes better able to function in its environment.

label: optics
description: The branch of physics that describes the behavior and properties of light and the interaction of light with matter.

label: phenotype
description: The assemblage of traits or outward appearance of an individual. It is the product of interactions between genes and between genes and the environment.

label: physiology
description: The study of the mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions of living organisms.

label: exposure
description: The act of subjecting someone or something to an influencing experience.

label: number fraction
description: The quotient of the number of particular entities [constituents] and the number of all constituents in the system.

label: enzyme activity
description: The rate of reaction catalyzed by an enzyme, usually expressed as micromoles of product formed or substrate transformed per minute.

label: metabolic process
description: Organic processes in a cell or organism that are necessary to sustain life. Cellular metabolism can be divided into two categories. Anabolism entails the construction of complex organic molecules from simpler precursors, while catabolism involves the breakdown of complex substances into simpler molecules

label: biochemical reaction
description: A chemical process, typically mediated by an enzyme, in which one or more substances (a substrate) are transformed by covalent modification into another substance(s) (a product) or in which the state of a substance is transformed.

label: age
description: How long something has existed; elapsed time since birth.

label: axis
description: A straight line through a body or figure that satisfies certain conditions.

label: classification
description: A method of generalization, the systematic arrangement of entities into classes or groups based on mutual similarity and certain differing characteristics.

label: magnitude
description: Greatness in size or extent; a number assigned to a quantity so that it may be compared with other quantities. (Dictionary.com)

label: sensitivity
description: The ability to respond to physical stimuli or to register small physical amounts or differences.

label: high
description: An elevated level or position or degree; greater than normal in degree or intensity or amount.

label: surface
description: The extended two-dimensional outer boundary of a three-dimensional object.

label: primary
description: Occurring first in time or sequence; original; of greatest rank or importance or value.

label: quantity
description: How much there is of something that you can measure; the total amount or number.

label: type
description: Something distinguishable as an identifiable class based on common qualities.

label: total
description: Pertaining to an entirety or whole, also constituting the full quantity or extent; complete; derived by addition.

label: lower
description: The bottom one of two.

label: duration
description: The period of time during which something continues.

label: location
description: A position, site, or point in space where something can be found.

label: mechanism
description: The means by which an effect is obtained.

label: upper
description: Higher in place or position; the topmost one of two.

label: small, smaller
description: Limited in number, quantity, magnitude or extent.

label: index
description: A numerical scale used to compare variables with one another or with some reference number; a number used to select an element of a list, vector, array or other sequence.

label: apical
description: Relating to or located at the tip (an apex).

label: change
description: The act of alteration or modification; changed or altered in form or character.

label: count
description: Determining the number or amount of something.

label: formation
description: The act of forming something or the structure formed.

label: function
description: The normal action performed by a structure or device.

label: increase
description: A process of becoming larger, more numerous, more important, or more likely.

label: longest
description: Having the greater length of two or the greatest length of several.

label: maximum
description: The largest possible quantity or degree.

label: minimum
description: The smallest possible quantity.

label: requirement
description: Something that is a necessary condition; something that is obligatory.

label: response
description: Any act or phenomena, or behavior, constituting a reply or reaction of a living organism or its part to some foregoing stimulus or agent.

label: parasite
description: Any organism that has a close, symbiotic relationship with a separate, host organism.

label: deficit
description: A lack or deficiency.

label: movement
description: A change in location or position.

label: specified
description: Clearly and explicitly stated.

label: taxon
description: Ranked categories for the classification of organisms according to their suspected evolutionary relationships.

label: flow
description: The continuous movement characteristic of a liquid or gas.

label: release
description: To make available; set free.

label: group
description: Any number of entities (members) considered as a unit.

label: compound
description: A substance formed by chemical union of two or more elements or ingredients in definite proportion by weight.

label: tolerance
description: The allowable deviation from a standard; a permissible difference.

label: external
description: Happening or arising or located outside or beyond some limits, or especially, some surface.

label: measured
description: Having been determined by measurement.

label: pH
description: Quantity of dimension one used to express on a scale from 0 to 14 the amount-of-substance concentration of hydrogen ion of dilute aqueous solution, calculated as the logarithm of the reciprocal of hydrogen-ion concentration in gram atoms per liter.

label: isotope
description: A form of a chemical element containing a specific number of neutrons and a specific atomic mass.

label: medium
description: A substance holding another substance in solution or suspension.

label: proportion
description: A part, fraction, share, or number considered in relation to the whole amount or number.

label: large, larger
description: Of considerable or relatively great size, extent, or capacity.

label: protrustion
description: (no definition)

label: avoidance
description: A conscious or unconscious refusal to encounter situations, activities, or objects; the act or practice of keeping away from or withdrawing from something.

label: performance
description: An action that is carried out or accomplished.

label: spread
description: The act of extending over a wider scope or expanse of space or time.

label: saturated
description: Impregnation of one substance by another to the greatest possible extent; that concentration of a dissolved substance that cannot be exceeded.

label: appendage
description: A natural prolongation or projection from a part of an organism either animal or plant; a part that is joined to something larger.

label: broad
description: Very large in expanse or scope; having great extent from one side to the other.

label: arrangement
description: The spatial property of the way in which something is placed.

label: defense
description: Protection from harm.

label: ambient
description: In or of the immediately surrounding area; relating to the immediate surroundings of something.

label: vapor
description: The gaseous state of matter that is a solid or liquid at normal room temperature.

label: cross section
description: A section created by a plane cutting a solid perpendicular to its longest axis.

label: consumption
description: The bodily process of taking in and using up something, especially the eating or drinking of something; The act of using something up to the point of depletion.

label: volume fraction
description: Quotient of the volume of a component and the total volume of the system containing the component.

label: gradient
description: A graded change in the magnitude of some physical quantity or dimension.

label: air
description: A mixture of gases making up the earth's atmosphere, consisting mainly of nitrogen, oxygen, argon, and carbon dioxide.

label: temporal
description: Of or relating to time or limited by time.

label: ability
description: The quality of being able to perform; a quality that permits or facilitates achievement or accomplishment.

label: spore
description: A reproductive cell (usually unicellular) capable of developing into an adult without fusion with another cell.

label: fascicle
description: A close cluster, as of flowers or leaves.

label: denominator
description: The divisor of a fraction.

label: climbing
description: The act of rising to a higher point.

label: diffusion
description: The movement of chemical species under the influence of a concentration difference and as a result of random thermal agitation. The species will move from the high concentration area to the low concentration area till the concentration is uniform in the whole phase.

label: photon
description: A single unit of electromagnetic radiation, generally considered to be a discrete particle having no mass or charge.

label: desiccation
description: The act of removing moisture from something.

label: basal
description: Relating to or located at the lowest portion of a structure.

label: wood
description: The hard, fibrous substance composing most of the stem and branches of a tree or shrub, and lying beneath the bark; the xylem.

label: resorption
description: A process in which a substance, such as tissue, is lost by being destroyed and then absorbed by the body.

label: rupture
description: Forcible tearing or disruption of tissue.

label: longest diameter
description: The longest possible length of a straight line passing through the center of a circular or spheroid object that connects two points on the circumference.

label: obtain
description: To come into possession of something.

label: microorganism
description: A microscopic organism. The term microorganism may refer to a prokaryote or eukaryote, and may be a unicellular or multicellular organism. All taxonomic kingdoms contain microorganisms.

label: inclusive
description: Including the stated limits.

label: visible light
description: Electromagnetic radiation in the portion of the spectrum from about 380 nm (violet) to 800 nm (red).

label: fresh specimen
description: A specimen that is output of a specimen creation process used for an investigation without storage.

label: categorical value specification
description: A value specification that is specifies one category out of a fixed number of nominal categories

label: organism
description: A material entity that is an individual living system, such as animal, plant, bacteria or virus, that is capable of replicating or reproducing, growth and maintenance in the right environment. An organism may be unicellular or made up, like humans, of many billions of cells divided into specialized tissues and organs.

label: storage
description: Any process in which a cell, substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, is maintained in a location and prevented from moving elsewhere.

label: light
description: [no definition]

label: genetic structures
description: [no definition]

label: genome size
description: [no definition]

label: seed dispersal
description: [no definition]

label: speed
description: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's scalar absolute value of the rate of change of the bearer's position.

label: colour / color
description: A composite chromatic quality composed of hue, saturation and intensity parts.

label: composition
description: A single physical entity inhering in an bearer by virtue of the bearer's quantities or relative ratios of subparts.

label: concentration
description: A quality inhering in a substance by virtue of the amount of the bearer's there is mixed with another substance.

label: distance
description: A quality that is the extent of space between two entities.

label: frequency
description: A physical quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the number of the bearer's repetitive actions in a particular time.

label: morphology
description: A quality of a single physical entity inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer's size or shape or structure.

label: shape
description: A morphological quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's ratios of distances between its features [points, edges, surfaces and also holes etc].

label: spatial pattern, distribution
description: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting repetition of placement of its parts.

label: pilosity
description: A texture quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having hair or bristles.

label: amount (presence or absence in organism)
description: The number of entities of this type that are part of the whole organism.

label: response to
description: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the whether the bearer's disposition to react to a stimulus or an agent.

label: size
description: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's physical magnitude.

label: height
description: A 1-D extent quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's vertical dimension of extension.

label: length
description: A 1-D extent quality which is equal to the distance between two points.

label: mass
description: A physical quality that inheres in a bearer by virtue of the proportion of the bearer's amount of matter.

label: orientation
description: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's placement which is defined by the angle between the bearer and an axis, or the angle between the bearer and another object.

label: position
description: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's spatial location relative to other objects in the vicinity.

label: structure
description: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's relative position, shape, arrangements and connectivity of an organism's various parts; the pattern underlying its form.

label: texture
description: A morphologic quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's relative size, organization and distribution of its surface elements or the representation or invention of the appearance of its surface; visual and tactile surface characteristics.

label: rate
description: A quality of a single process inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's occurrence per unit time.

label: time
description: A quality in which events occur in sequence.

label: viability
description: An organismal quality inhering in a bearer or a population by virtue of the bearer's disposition to survive and develop normally or the number of surviving individuals in a given population.

label: maturity
description: A quality of a single physical entity which is held by a bearer when the latter exhibits a state of growth, differentiation, or development.

label: dark
description: A color brightness which is relatively low

label: irregular
description: A spatial pattern inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's magnitude of or the relationships between its repeated parts lack consistency.

label: female
description: A biological sex quality inhering in an individual or a population that only produces gametes that can be fertilised by male gametes.

label: male
description: A biological sex quality inhering in an individual or a population whose sex organs contain only male gametes.

label: coiled
description: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being curled or wound [especially in concentric rings or spirals].

label: flat
description: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having a horizontal surface without a slope, tilt, or curvature.

label: pinnate
description: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having leaflets or leaflets-like structures on each side of a common axis.

label: glabrous
description: A pilosity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's lack of hairs or bristles.

label: hairy
description: A pilosity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being covered with hair or hairlike projections.

label: absent
description: A quality denoting the lack of an entity.

label: present
description: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's existence.

label: increased length, long
description: A length quality which is relatively large.

label: increased thickness, thickened; high thickness; stout
formatted label and identifier: increased thickness, thickened; high thickness; stout [PATO:0000591]
description: A thickness which is relatively high.

label: decreased width
description: A width which is relatively small.

label: increased width
description: A width which is relatively large.

label: female sterile
description: A female fertility quality inhering in a female by virtue of the bearer's being incapable of initiating, sustaining, or supporting reproduction.

label: thickness
description: A 1-D extent quality which is equal to the dimension through an object as opposed to its length or width.

label: volume
description: A 3-D extent quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's amount of 3-dimensional space it occupies.

label: width
description: A 1-D extent quality which is equal to the distance from one side of an object to another side which is opposite.

label: fertile
description: A fertility quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being capable of initiating, sustaining, or supporting reproduction.

label: symmetry
description: A pattern quality of inhering in a bearer by virtue of the correspondence in size, shape, and relative position of the bearer's parts on opposite sides of a dividing line or median plane or about a center or axis.

label: permeable
description: A permeability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being capable to be permeated or pervaded by a gas or liquid (as by osmosis or diffusion).

label: physical quality
description: A quality of a physical entity that exists through action of continuants at the physical level of organisation in relation to other entities.

label: mass density, density
description: A physical quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of some influence is exerted by the bearer's mass per unit size.

label: energy
description: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's capacity to do work.

label: power
description: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's rate of doing work.

label: pressure
description: A physical quality that inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's amount of force per unit area it exerts.

label: work
description: A physical quality which is equal to the energy transferred by a force to a moving object.

label: efficiency
description: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of ratio of the bearer's output to the bearer's input.

label: elasticity
description: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to recover its size and shape after deformation in any way.

label: strain
description: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the relative change in the bearer's length or the bearer's volume when being stretched or squashed.

label: force
description: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's rate of change of momentum.

label: resistance to
description: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to resist to a stimulus.

label: juvenile
description: A maturity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue the bearer's being not fully grown or developed.

label: proximal to
description: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being located more centrally than another entity.

label: serrated
description: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of having sharp straight-edged teeth pointing to the apex.

label: strength
description: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's power or force.

label: distal to
description: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being located further from a more centrally located entity.

label: duration
description: A process quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's magnitude of the temporal extent between the starting and ending point.

label: area
description: A 2-D extent quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's two dimensional extent.

label: actinomorphic
description: A symmetry quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being capable of division into symmetrical halves by any longitudinal plane passing through the axis.

label: diameter
description: A length quality which is equal to the length of any straight line segment that passes through the center of a circle and whose endpoints are on the circular boundary.

label: hermaphrodite
description: A biological sex quality inhering in an organism or a population with both male and female sexual organs in one individual.

label: area density
description: A density quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of some influence exerted by the bearer's mass on a given area.

label: volume density
description: A density quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of some influence exerted by the bearer's mass on a given volume.

label: spiny
description: A surface feature shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having spines, thorns or similar thin projections on its surface.

label: ploidy
description: A cellular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's number of homologous sets of chromosomes in the nucleus or primary chromosome-containing compartment of the cell, each set essentially coding for all the biological traits of the organism.

label: diploid
description: A ploidy quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having two copies (homologs) of each chromosome, usually one from the mother and one from the father.

label: alive
description: A viability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's condition before death.

label: dead
description: A viability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the cessation of the bearer's life.

label: ratio; proportion
description: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's magnitude in respect to a related entity.

label: senescent
description: A time quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's growing old; aging.

label: soluble in
description: A solubility quality inhering in a substance by virtue of the bearer's disposition to dissolve in a liquid.

label: insoluble in
description: A solubility quality inhering in a substance by virtue of the bearer's inability of a substance to dissolve in a liquid.

label: has number of
description: The number of parts of a particular type that the bearer entity has. This is a relational quality, and thus holds between two entities: the bearer of the quality, and the type of parts.

label: conductivity
description: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to transmit of an entity through a medium.

label: curvature
description: A surface shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting a degree of bending.

label: depth
description: A 1-D extent quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's downward or backward or inward dimension.

label: turgor
description: A structural quality inhering in a cell or blood vessel or capillary by virtue of the bearer's being in a rigid state of fullness resulting from pressure of the contents against the wall or membrane.

label: attached to
description: An attachment quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's connection or association with another entity.

label: mature
description: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting complete growth, differentiation, or development.

label: 1-D extent
description: A size quality inhering in an bearer by virtue of the bearer's extension in one dimension.

label: 2-D extent
description: A size quality inhering in an bearer by virtue of the bearer's extension in two dimensions.

label: 3-D extent
description: A size quality inhering in an bearer by virtue of the bearer's extension in three dimensions.

label: perimeter
description: An 1-D extent quality inhering in two-dimensional bearer by virtue of being equal to the distance around it.

label: shedability
description: An organismal quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to lose an entitity by natural process.

label: deciduous
description: A quality inhering in a plant by virtue of the bearer's disposition to shed foliage.

label: evergreen
description: A quality inhering in a plant by virtue of the bearer's disposition to retain foliage.

label: dry
description: A wetness quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's not being covered by a liquid.

label: vertical
description: A spatial pattern inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being situated at right angles to the horizon.

label: horizontal
description: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being in the plane of the horizon.

label: phenotypic sex
description: An organismal quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's physical expression of sexual characteristics.

label: surface feature shape
description: This quality either inheres directly in the surface, or in the entity that has the surface. For example, to say that a particular fly wing is curved is shorthand for saying the wing has a surface which is curved. A surface shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's shape of features present on its surface or outer shell.

label: whorled
description: A spatial pattern inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being in opposition round a common axis.

label: revolute
description: A curled quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's edges of its surface being rolled backwards spirally on each side.

label: lobed
description: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being partly divided into a determinate number of regions.

label: organismal quality
description: A quality that inheres in an entire organism or part of an organism.

label: branchiness
description: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the degree to which there are subdivisions or offshoots in a bearer entity.

label: abaxial
description: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being away from or on the opposite side of the central axis.

label: adaxial
description: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being located on the side nearest to the axis of an organ or organism.

label: recurved
description: A curvature quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being curved backward or inward.

label: edge shape
description: [no definition]

label: tension
description: A physical quality that pertains by virtue of a pulling force that is directed away from the bearer and attempts to stretch or elongate the bearer.

label: angle
description: An orientation inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's placement at an angle.

label: fleshy
description: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer resembling or containing flesh.

label: herbaceous
description: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's upper parts die back to the rootstock at the end of the growing season.

label: active
description: A quality of an physical object that is currently realizing one of its functions.

label: waxy
description: Presence of long chain aliphatic lipids on the surface of an organism.

label: perpendicular to
description: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being located at a right angle relative to another entity.

label: slit-like
description: Shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer exhibiting a narrow and elongate opening.

label: differentiated from
description: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being morphologically distinguishable from another entity.

label: salinity
description: An osmolarity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the total amount of ionic salts dissolved in the bearer.

label: curled
description: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having parallel chains in undulate fashion on the border.

label: functional
description: A functionality quality held by the bearer when the latter is able to perform a regular function(s).

label: population
description: A collection of organisms, all of the same species, that live in the same place.

label: whole plant
description: A plant structure [PO:0005679] which is a whole organism.

label: plant cuticle
description: A portion of plant substance [PO:0025161] composed of cutin [PO:0025385], a polyester matrix of hydroxy- and hydroxy epoxy fatty acids C16 and C18 chains, embedded and overlayed with cuticular wax [PO:0025386] and forming a layer on the surface of a plant epidermis [PO:0005679]. The plant cuticle is produced in and secreted by epidermal cells [PO:0004013] of leaves [PO:0025034], stems [PO:0009047], fruits [PO:0009001], and other aerial plant structures. It has as parts an inner cuticle proper [PO:0025387] and an outer layer of epicuticular wax [PO:0025388].

label: vascular system
description: A maximal portion of vascular tissue [PO:0009015] in a whole plant [PO:0000003], collective plant structure [PO:0025497], multi-tissue plant structure [PO:0025496], or cardinal part of multi-tissue plant structure [PO:0025498].

label: shoot axis apex
description: A shoot axis (PO:0025029) that is the most distal part of a shoot system (PO:0009006) and has as parts a shoot apical meristem (PO:0020148) and the youngest primordia (PO:0025127).

label: leaf lamina abaxial epidermis
description: A portion of leaf lamina epidermis that covers the abaxial/lower surface of a leaf lamina.

label: leaf lamina adaxial epidermis
description: A portion of leaf lamina epidermis that covers the adaxial/upper surface of a leaf lamina.

label: bud
description: An undeveloped shoot system (PO:0009006).

label: flower bud
description: A bud that develops into a flower.

label: parenchyma cell
description: A relatively unspecialized ground tissue cell with a nucleate protoplast.

label: sclerenchyma cell
description: A ground tissue cell [PO:0025030] with a lignified secondary cell wall.

label: trichome
description: A unicellular or multicellular plant structure (PO:0009011) that forms a non-sclerified outgrowth from the epidermis (PO:0005679).

label: guard cell
description: One of a pair of cells flanking the stomatal pore.

label: tracheids
description: A tracheary element [PO:0000290] that has no perforations in its cell wall.

label: vascular leaf expansion stage
description: During this stage leaf shaping (GO:0010358) occurs which is defined as the developmental process that pertains to the organization of a leaf in three-dimensional space once the structure has initially formed. A vascular leaf development stage (PO:0025570) during which vascular leaf size increases primarily through cell expansion.

label: plant embryo true leaf formation stage
formatted label and identifier: plant embryo true leaf formation stage [PO:0001095]
description: A true leaf is vascular leaf [PO:0009025] that forms after the formation of the cotyledons [PO:0020030] or a coleoptile [PO:0020033]. Not all species form true leaves in the plant embryo development stage [PO:0007631]. If it occurs, a plant embryo true leaf formation stage is preceded by either a plant embryo cotyledonary stage [PO:0001078] or a plant embryo coleoptilar stage [PO:0001094], depending upon the species.

label: stomatal complex
description: A portion of shoot system epidermis [PO:0006035] that has as parts two guard cells [PO:0000293] and a stomatal pore [PO:0008032]. May also contain subsidiary cells [PO:0000284].

label: epidermal cell
description: A native plant cell [PO:0025606] that is part of a portion of epidermis [PO:0005679].

label: sapwood
description: A portion of secondary xylem [PO:0005848] that has as parts living secondary xylem parenchyma cells.

label: bark
description: A portion of plant tissue [PO:0009007] outside the vascular cambium [PO:0005598] or the xylem [PO:0005352]; in older trees may be divided into dead outer bark and living inner bark, which consists of secondary ...

label: axial secondary xylem parenchyma
description: A portion of secondary xylem parenchyma [PO:0004532] that is part of an axial system [PO:0025410] and has as parts axial secondary xylem parenchyma cells [PO:0004526].

label: ray secondary xylem parenchyma
description: A portion of secondary xylem parenchyma [PO:0004532] that is part of a ray system [PO:0025411] and has as parts ray secondary xylem parenchyma cells [PO:0004527].

label: anther dehiscence zone
description: A dehiscence zone (PO:0025092) that is part of an anther (PO:0009066). Extends along the entire length of the anther and is observed as an indentation between the locules of each theca. Upon anther maturation, cell separation within the dehiscence zone allows the anther wall to break open and pollen to be released.

label: hypodermis
description: A portion of ground tissue [PO:0025059] that is the outermost layer of a portion of cortex [PO:0005708].

label: xylem
description: A portion of vascular tissue [PO:0009015] that has as part one or more tracheary elements [PO:0000290].

label: spongy mesophyll
description: Leaf mesophyll parenchyma characterized by little elongated cells, that are not closely packed and have conspicuous intercellular spaces.

label: palisade mesophyll
description: Parenchyma containing closely packed elongated chlorenchymatous cells oriented perpendicular to the leaf surface and which are active in photosynthesis

label: epidermis
description: A portion of plant tissue [PO:0009007] composed of epidermal cells [PO:0004013] that develops from the protoderm [PO:0006210] and covers the surface of a plant structure [PO:0009011].

label: wood, secondary xylem
description: A portion of xylem [PO:0005352] tissue that develops from a vascular cambium [PO:0005598].

label: mesophyll
